# <%= current_page.data.title %>

This page summarises what we learned from restore testing and where to find deeper technical detail.

## Practical findings for DR responders

- Restore speed is usually dominated by DB replay and index build, not vault trigger time.
- Small SKUs can significantly increase restore duration.
- Increasing SKU and storage size can improve restore time.
- Scale-up caveat: once the database has been scaled up, you cannot downgrade it back to a lower SKU/storage allocation on Flexible Server.
- Parallel restore and tuned session settings can materially reduce replay time.

## Operational lessons

- Prefer automation first for consistency and evidence capture.
- Keep manual portal path documented and tested for contingency.
- If vault restore succeeded but replay failed, use `database-only` rerun mode.
- Keep incident logs with exact restore point, timings, and parameter values.

## Known platform constraints to account for

- Managed PostgreSQL role replay restrictions and expected role errors.
- No useful restore path from `_tablespace.sql` on Flexible Server.
- `_schema.sql` is not required when schema is already in per-database dump files.
- PostgreSQL version support/EOL constraints affect restore target provisioning.

